          "title": "The arrow code: Providence spoken in archery",
          "body": "The arrow signal (20:20-22, 36-38) is the chapter's most elegant narrative device. Jonathan has designed a simple binary: if the arrow lands near — 'it is safe, no harm' (20:21); if the arrow flies beyond — 'the LORD has sent you away' (20:22). What is striking is the theological freight loaded onto an archery exercise. The near-arrow outcome is simply *shalom*; but the far-arrow outcome is not 'Saul intends to kill you' — it is 'the LORD has sent you away.' Jonathan has already reframed David's expulsion from court as a divine sending. God is not merely permitting what Saul's rage is forcing; He is dispatching His anointed to the next stage of His purpose. The signal is executed in 20:36-38 with understated precision: the arrow flies past the boy; Jonathan calls after him; the lad retrieves the arrow without understanding a word of what has been communicated (20:39). Providence operates on two levels simultaneously — the boy sees only archery, while David hears a verdict about his life."
