          "title": "The farewell: weeping more than one another",
          "body": "The chapter's final scene (20:41-42) is one of Scripture's most emotionally concentrated partings. David rises from hiding, falls on his face three times in covenant prostration, and the two men kiss and weep. The narrator's precision is exact: 'David wept the more' (20:41). This is not mere sentimentality. David weeps more because he is the one being sent away — into the wilderness, into years of fugitive life, into a future that will not include this friend's daily presence. Jonathan weeps, but Jonathan is going back into the city. His grief is real; David's loss is deeper. Yet it is Jonathan who speaks the farewell, and the farewell is not a lament — it is a covenant reaffirmation: 'Go in safety, inasmuch as we have sworn to each other in the name of the LORD' (20:42). The ground of the parting is not what they feel but what they have sworn. The LORD is between them and their descendants forever. Tears are appropriate; but the oath endures past the tears. Both men rise and depart — David into the wilderness, Jonathan into the city — and the narrator does not sweeten the ending. The chapter closes on separation, not reunion."
